<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="532" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1708,1987]" pageId="11" pageNumber="532">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1708,1734]" pageId="11" pageNumber="532">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1793" box="[660,800,1709,1735]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Ancyloscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="532" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiformis">
<emphasis box="[660,800,1709,1735]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="532">A. apiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it can be separated by the black scape and pedicel in both sexes, and the flagellum is also dark in the males; the pronotal lobe is also dark (
<figureCitation box="[1214,1301,1745,1771]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,905,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-290@12.[151,1435,905,1889]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Males, A. apiformis species group, head, frontal view. A, A. apiformis (Fabricius). B, A. nigricornis Rodríguez &amp; Roig-Alsina. C, A. romeroi (Holmberg). D, A. saltensis Rodríguez &amp; Roig-Alsina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4897156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4897156/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="532">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
). This is the smallest species in 
<collectingCountry box="[363,477,1781,1807]" name="Argentina" pageId="11" pageNumber="532">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, the length of the forewing being 
<quantity box="[850,988,1780,1807]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" metricValueMax="5.7" metricValueMin="3.9" pageId="11" pageNumber="532" unit="mm" value="4.8" valueMax="5.7" valueMin="3.9">3.9–5.7 mm</quantity>
. The inner tooth of the hind basitarsus is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1793" box="[343,481,1817,1843]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Ancyloscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="532" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiformis">
<emphasis box="[343,481,1817,1843]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="532">A. apiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but less prominent and not hooked (
<figureCitation box="[895,996,1817,1843]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1197,1221]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,181,1173]" captionTargetId="figure-30@14.[154,1434,181,1173]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 11. Males, A. apiformis species group, posterior basitarsus, ventral view.A, A. apiformis (Fabricius). B, A. nigricornis Rodríguez &amp; Roig-Alsina. C, A. romeroi (Holmberg). D, A. saltensis Rodríguez &amp; Roig-Alsina. Scale lines = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4897162" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4897162/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="532">Fig. 11B</figureCitation>
). The hidden sterna and genital capsule have been drawn by Rodríguez and Roig-Alsina (2004).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
